title: Voter turnout in UK elections 1918 to 2019
summary: This line chart has an x axis representing Year and a y axis representing Voter turnout, with a total of 29 data points. The chart has 6 significant trends.
The longest trend is extremely positive which exists from 2019 to 2001.
Also, the next significant trend is slightly positive which exists from 2001 to 1983.
In a similar manner, the next significant trend is moderately positive which exists from 1983 to 1970.
Correspondingly, the next significant trend is moderately positive which exists from 1970 to 1955.
Correspondingly, the next significant trend is extremely positive which exists from 1955 to 1935.
Correspondingly, the next significant trend is moderately positive which exists from 1935 to 1923.
gold: In the 2019 United Kingdom General Election , voter turnout was 67.3 percent of eligible voters , a 1.5 percent drop compared with the previous general election in 2017 . Between 1922 and 1997 voter turnout never fell below 70 percent , but in 2001 it dropped to just 59.4 percent . Since that low point , voter turnout has gradually recovered and reached 72.2 percent in the Brexit Referendum of 2016 , which is still some way off the peak of 83.9 percent recorded in the 1950 General Election .
